1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,360
INSTRUCTOR: Now let's
focus on the intuition

2
00:00:02,360 --> 00:00:08,080
behind constructing U. We wanted
to cover two distinct scenarios.

3
00:00:08,080 --> 00:00:11,600
In the first scenario,
John has a worse prognosis

4
00:00:11,600 --> 00:00:14,760
than his neighbors,
Mary, Peter, and Tom.

5
00:00:14,760 --> 00:00:19,440
John's bad outcome is mostly
explained by observed features.

6
00:00:19,440 --> 00:00:22,480
The model already
expected him to be

7
00:00:22,480 --> 00:00:27,000
in higher risk than similarly
treated patients who did well.

8
00:00:27,000 --> 00:00:30,360
In other words, there is little
residual unobserved burden

9
00:00:30,360 --> 00:00:31,680
to explain.

10
00:00:31,680 --> 00:00:35,500
In this case, we want his
unobserved factor, U John,

11
00:00:35,500 --> 00:00:37,160
to be low.

12
00:00:37,160 --> 00:00:40,560
In the second scenario,
John has better prognosis

13
00:00:40,560 --> 00:00:42,280
than his neighbors.

14
00:00:42,280 --> 00:00:46,260
John did worse than expected
given his observed prognosis,

15
00:00:46,260 --> 00:00:50,600
so his bad outcome is not
explained by observed features.

16
00:00:50,600 --> 00:00:53,800
That gap is precisely what
we call unobserved prognostic

17
00:00:53,800 --> 00:00:58,060
burden, so we want his
unobserved factor, U John,

18
00:00:58,060 --> 00:01:00,120
to be high.

19
00:01:00,120 --> 00:01:04,480
Now which formula can capture
these scenarios successfully?

20
00:01:04,480 --> 00:01:07,480
We score everyone with a
prognostic model trained

21
00:01:07,480 --> 00:01:09,320
on the untreated cohort.

22
00:01:09,320 --> 00:01:12,820
So the scores reflect
baseline disease scores.

23
00:01:12,820 --> 00:01:16,980
And we find John's K nearest
treated neighbors who

24
00:01:16,980 --> 00:01:20,940
had good outcomes, in this
case as we said Mary, Peter,

25
00:01:20,940 --> 00:01:23,820
and Tom, so K equals 3.

26
00:01:23,820 --> 00:01:28,660
We compare John's predicted
risk, P John, to the average

27
00:01:28,660 --> 00:01:31,580
predicted risk of his neighbors.

28
00:01:31,580 --> 00:01:34,580
The raw quantity
that gives U John

29
00:01:34,580 --> 00:01:40,740
is the difference between P
John and the average baseline

30
00:01:40,740 --> 00:01:45,220
prognosis of his neighbors,
which we later normalize

31
00:01:45,220 --> 00:01:49,420
into 0, 1 to get U tilde John.

32
00:01:49,420 --> 00:01:53,900
Now how does this quantity
satisfy our two scenarios?

33
00:01:53,900 --> 00:01:57,620
In the first scenario,
John has worse prognosis

34
00:01:57,620 --> 00:01:59,180
than his neighbors.

35
00:01:59,180 --> 00:02:04,060
If P John is lower than
his neighbor's average,

36
00:02:04,060 --> 00:02:10,860
then after normalization,
U tilde John lands near 0.

37
00:02:10,860 --> 00:02:14,220
In the second scenario,
John has better prognosis

38
00:02:14,220 --> 00:02:15,790
than his neighbors.

39
00:02:15,790 --> 00:02:20,030
If P John is higher, meaning
he looked healthier on observed

40
00:02:20,030 --> 00:02:24,230
covariates, then U--

41
00:02:24,230 --> 00:02:28,550
U tilde John increases
and moves toward 1.

42
00:02:28,550 --> 00:02:31,190
We perform the
exact same approach

43
00:02:31,190 --> 00:02:34,530
for all the untreated patients
with bad outcomes, too,

44
00:02:34,530 --> 00:02:38,950
and we again normalize
their unobserved quantity.

45
00:02:38,950 --> 00:02:42,190
There are a few design
choices we need to make.

46
00:02:42,190 --> 00:02:44,350
First are the prognostic model.

47
00:02:44,350 --> 00:02:47,590
Linear Cox models trained
on untreated patients

48
00:02:47,590 --> 00:02:50,990
work well and avoid overfitting.

49
00:02:50,990 --> 00:02:52,750
Second, the number of neighbors.

50
00:02:52,750 --> 00:02:57,710
We avoid choosing a very small
number of neighbors like 1

51
00:02:57,710 --> 00:02:59,550
due to instability.

52
00:02:59,550 --> 00:03:02,870
Values like 3 to 5
are typically robust.

53
00:03:02,870 --> 00:03:07,470
Empirically, road three is
robust across reasonable choices

54
00:03:07,470 --> 00:03:10,290
of prognostic model,
number of neighbors,

55
00:03:10,290 --> 00:03:12,990
and neighborhood density.

56
00:03:12,990 --> 00:03:15,930
Once we have our
utility quantity,

57
00:03:15,930 --> 00:03:18,710
we do not insert it
into the matching step.

58
00:03:18,710 --> 00:03:21,470
It is strongly correlated
with the outcome

59
00:03:21,470 --> 00:03:24,050
and would distort distances.

60
00:03:24,050 --> 00:03:28,230
Instead following the frequency
weighting approach or row

61
00:03:28,230 --> 00:03:30,570
weighting approach
from road one,

62
00:03:30,570 --> 00:03:33,170
we compute a single
scalar weight

63
00:03:33,170 --> 00:03:36,290
for the treated group
with good outcomes

64
00:03:36,290 --> 00:03:40,930
so that the weighted
mean of U tilde

65
00:03:40,930 --> 00:03:45,690
becomes matched between
treated and untreated arms.

66
00:03:45,690 --> 00:03:48,770
This is the minimal control
that balances the latent factors

67
00:03:48,770 --> 00:03:51,490
distribution between
the two treatment arms

68
00:03:51,490 --> 00:03:54,530
without overfitting
small cohorts.

69
00:03:54,530 --> 00:03:57,930
After waiting, we fit a
multivariable Cox model

70
00:03:57,930 --> 00:04:01,570
on the transformed cohort
including treatment and baseline

71
00:04:01,570 --> 00:04:05,610
covariates to estimate
the final hazard ratio.

72
00:04:05,610 --> 00:04:09,570
So to summarize, the
three steps are we first

73
00:04:09,570 --> 00:04:12,410
perform road one
prognostic matching

74
00:04:12,410 --> 00:04:14,890
to fix observed confounding.

75
00:04:14,890 --> 00:04:19,050
Second, we compute U
tilde and balance it

76
00:04:19,050 --> 00:04:22,210
across treatment arms
via scalar weight.

77
00:04:22,210 --> 00:04:25,930
And, three, we run a Cox
model on the balanced cohort

78
00:04:25,930 --> 00:04:28,410
to obtain the hazard ratio.

79
00:04:28,410 --> 00:04:31,680
That's road three end to end.